3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Orderly Network calculates funding rates hourly based on the premium/discount between perpetual and spot prices across their shared order book. The rate is distributed among all frontend partners using the infrastructure, creating a unified funding mechanism. Funding payments occur every hour at the top of each hour, with rates typically ranging from -0.375% to +0.375% annually. The shared liquidity model means funding rates reflect aggregate market sentiment across multiple DEX interfaces rather than isolated exchange dynamics."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","SOL","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SOL/USDT represents one of the highest volume pairs on Orderly Network, benefiting from the protocol's deep SOL market maker relationships. The pair's funding rates often diverge from CEX rates due to different user bases and the decentralized nature of position distribution across frontend partners. This divergence creates consistent arbitrage opportunities, particularly during Solana ecosystem events when DEX users show different sentiment patterns than CEX traders."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SOL/USDT funding rates on Orderly Network have shown distinct patterns influenced by the platform's shared liquidity model. During Q4 2023, rates averaged 0.015% per funding period, with notable spikes during Solana ecosystem announcements reaching 0.08% hourly. The hourly funding frequency creates more granular rate adjustments compared to 8-hour CEX cycles. Weekend funding rates tend to be lower due to reduced DEX trading activity, while rates spike during US trading hours when frontend partner activity peaks. The shared order book architecture means funding rates reflect consensus across multiple DEX interfaces, often leading to smoother rate transitions than isolated exchanges."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Cross-Exchange Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Orderly Network's SOL/USDT funding rates frequently deviate from major CEXs by 0.02-0.05% per period, creating arbitrage opportunities. The platform's 0.02% maker fees and 0.05% taker fees must be factored into arbitrage calculations alongside gas costs for NEAR/EVM operations. Funding rate convergence typically occurs within 2-4 hours, providing windows for profitable arbitrage. The shared liquidity model means arbitrageurs can access the same rates across multiple frontend partners, reducing execution complexity. Most profitable opportunities arise when CEX funding turns negative while Orderly maintains positive rates, especially during SOL staking reward distributions."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Management Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Trading SOL/USDT perpetuals on Orderly Network involves unique risks related to the shared infrastructure model. Frontend partner failures can impact access to positions, though the underlying order book remains on-chain. The platform's dependence on NEAR/EVM bridge security adds smart contract risk compared to CEX trading. Funding rate arbitrage requires careful timing due to hourly settlements versus traditional 8-hour cycles, increasing frequency of required actions. Liquidity can vary significantly across different time zones as frontend partner activity fluctuates, potentially affecting execution during volatile periods."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does Orderly Network's shared liquidity affect SOL/USDT funding rates?","answer":"The shared order book aggregates positions across multiple frontend partners, creating funding rates that reflect broader DEX market sentiment rather than individual exchange dynamics. This typically results in more stable rates but can create arbitrage opportunities when DEX and CEX user sentiment diverges."},{"question":"What are the optimal times for SOL/USDT funding arbitrage on Orderly Network?","answer":"Best opportunities typically occur during US trading hours when frontend activity peaks and during Solana ecosystem events. The hourly funding cycle creates more frequent arbitrage windows compared to 8-hour CEX cycles, but requires more active monitoring."},{"question":"How do Orderly Network's fees impact SOL/USDT funding arbitrage profitability?","answer":"With 0.02% maker and 0.05% taker fees, funding rate spreads need to exceed 0.07-0.10% per period to remain profitable after costs. The frequent hourly settlements can accumulate fees quickly, making longer-term arbitrage positions more cost-effective."},{"question":"What risks are unique to SOL perpetuals on decentralized exchanges like Orderly?","answer":"Key risks include frontend partner dependencies, smart contract risks from NEAR/EVM bridge infrastructure, and potential liquidity fragmentation across time zones. Unlike CEXs, you're also exposed to on-chain congestion affecting settlement timing."}]}]
